On this day in 1775, Benedict Arnold sets his sights on Fort St. John’s, near the Canadian border. He would soon seize the largest British warship in the area! It would become the first of many #American ships to bear the name #Enterprise. About one week earlier, Arnold and #EthanAllen had captured Fort #Ticonderoga in #NewYork. Arnold felt that his grip on the forts at the southern end of Lake Champlain was tenuous. The British still controlled Fort St. John’s, about 120 miles away. They also had the largest warship in the area: the British sloop HMS George. Fortunately, one of Arnold’s men soon arrived at Ticonderoga with a captured schooner. Arnold renamed her Liberty. “We immediately fixed her with four carriage, and six-swivel guns,” he wrote. He departed for St. John’s, arriving within 30 miles of the fort on May 17. Arnold later reported on the ease with which he “surprised and took a sergeant and his party of 12 men” at the garrison the next morning. Their Captain was gone, but he was expected back soon with more men and supplies. It seemed to Arnold “a mere interposition of #Providence that we arrived in so fortunate an hour.” Arnold also captured the warship George—without firing a single shot! His men loaded her with supplies, then destroyed other boats so as to hamper the British pursuit. “Just at the completion of our business,” one of Arnold’s men wrote, “a fine gale arose from the North; we directly hoisted sail, and returned in triumph.” “We are masters of the Lake,” Arnold soon reported. He renamed the captured ship Enterprise. P.S. The picture is an artist’s conception of the latest U.S. ship to bear the name “Enterprise.” Construction of this ship is expected to begin soon.
